{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643671"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:56:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:56:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.62,0.04,0.19,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63834"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA cervical spine X-ray is performed, revealing a vertebra with a prominent dens, large flat superior facets, and a large spinous process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following spinal levels is most likely described by these characteristics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C1","C2","C3","C7","C8"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vertebra described in the stem is the \u003Cstrong\u003EC2\u003C/strong\u003E vertebra, also known as the axis. It is characterised by the presence of the dens (odontoid process), which projects superiorly and articulates with the atlas (C1) to allow for rotation of the head. The large, flat superior facets of C2 articulate with the inferior facets of C1, facilitating head movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1\u003C/strong\u003E, or the atlas, lacks a body and spinous process, and instead has anterior and posterior arches. It supports the skull and allows for nodding motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC3\u003C/strong\u003E and other typical cervical vertebrae have smaller spinous processes and lack the dens, which is unique to C2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E is known as the vertebra prominens due to its long, non-bifid spinous process, but it does not have a dens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E is not a vertebra; it refers to the eighth cervical nerve, which exits between the C7 and T1 vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The second cervical vertebra, C2, is characterised by the presence of the dens, which allows for rotation of the head.","C2 has large, flat superior facets that articulate with the atlas (C1) to support head movement.","The spinous process of C2 is large and bifid, providing attachment for muscles and ligaments."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T21:25:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T00:09:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10719"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78472"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"